# {{lb|en|Christianity}} A member of any of the [[Christian]] [[church]]es which identify with the theology of {{w|Martin Luther}}.
#: {{ux|en|The split between the '''Lutherans''' and the Roman Catholics began with the [[w:Diet of Worms#Edict of Worms|Edict of Worms]] in 1521.}}
#* {{quote-book|author=William Rainolds [''i.e.'', [[w:William Reynolds (theologian)|William Reynolds]]]|chapter=VVherein is Refelled{{sic|Repelled?}} M. VV. Ansvvere to Certaine Places of S[aint] [[w:John Chrysostom|Chrysostome]] Touching the Real Presence and Sacrifice|title=A Refvtation of Svndry Reprehensions, Cavils, and False Sleightes, by which M. [[w:William Whitaker (theologian)|[William] Whitaker]] Laboureth to Deface the Late English Translation and Catholike Annotations of the New Testament, and the Booke of Discouery of Heretical Corruptions|location=Paris|publisher=[s.n.]|year=1583|pages=222–223|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=g9M7AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA223|oclc=8433986|passage=[I]f you had bene but ſo conuerſante in Caluine &#91;{{w|John Calvin}}&#93; as your profeſsion requireth, you could not ſo far haue bene ouerſeene in this eaſie diſtinction knowen to Catholike, '''Lutheran''' and [[Zwinglian|Zuinglian]], although when Caluine wrote thus, perhaps he was more then halfe a '''Lutheran''', and not ſo far gone in [[Zwinglianism|Zuinglianiſme]] as after.}}
#* {{quote-book|author=William Robertson|authorlink=William Robertson (historian)|chapter=The Siege of Magdeburg [marginal note]|title=The History of the Reign of the [[w:Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Charles V]]|edition=new|location=London|publisher=Printed for [[w:William Strahan (publisher)|W[illiam] Strahan]]; [[w:Thomas Cadell (publisher)|T[homas] Cadell]], in the [[w:Strand, London|Strand]]; Edinburgh: J. Balfour|year=1772|volume=IV|section=book X|page=40|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=BrfBqGHLzVQC&pg=PA40|oclc=969042486|passage={{...}} George of Mecklenburg, a younger brother of the reigning Duke, an active and ambitious Prince, collected a conſiderable number of thoſe ſoldiers of fortune who had accompanied Henry of Brunſwick in all his wild enterprizes; and though a zealous '''Lutheran''' himſelf, invaded the territories of the Magdeburgers, hoping that, by the merit of this ſervice, he might procure ſome part of their domains to be allotted to him as an eſtabliſhment.}}
#* {{quote-book|author=Thomas M[artin] Lindsay|authorlink=Thomas Martin Lindsay|chapter=From the Diet of Speyer, 1526, to the Religious Peace of Augsburg, 1555|title=A History of the Reformation|series=International Theological Library|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher={{w|Charles Scribner's Sons}}|year=1906|volume=I (The Reformation in Germany from Its Beginning to the Religious Peace of Augsburg)|pages=345–346|pageurl=https://archive.org/stream/historyofreformat190600lind#page/345/mode/1up/|oclc=3960339|passage=At this memorable [[w:Diet of Speyer (1529)|Diet of Speyer]] (1529), a compact Roman Catholic majority faced a weak Lutheran minority. The Emperor, through his commissioners, declared at the outset that he abolished, "by his imperial and absolute authority (''Machtvollkommenheit'')," the clause in the ordinance of 1526 on which the '''Lutherans''' had relied when they founded their territorial Churches; it had been the cause, he said, "of much ill counsel and misundestanding." {{...}} It was this ordinance which called forth the celebrated {{smallcaps|Protest}}, from which comes the name ''Protestant''. The Protest was read in the Diet on the day (April 19th, 1529) when all concessions to the '''Lutherans''' had been refused.}}

